  "prompt": "What is the acceptable TDS level of drinking water?",
  "response": "TDS stands for Total Dissolved Solids, which refers to the amount of inorganic and organic materials, like salts and minerals, present in water. The acceptable TDS level for drinking water varies depending on the country and regulatory agency, but generally falls within the following ranges:\n\n1. World Health Organization (WHO): The WHO recommends a maximum TDS level of 500 mg/L (milligrams per liter) for potable water.\n2. United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA): The EPA's secondary drinking water standard sets the ideal TDS level at 500 mg/L, but it is not enforceable.\n3. European Union: The EU sets a maximum limit of 1,500 mg/L for TDS in drinking water.\n\nWhile water with TDS levels above these guidelines may be safe to drink, it could have an unpleasant taste, odor, or appearance. In some cases, high TDS levels can indicate the presence of potentially harmful contaminants. If you are concerned about your water quality, it is advisable to have it tested by a certified laboratory and consult with a water treatment professional.",
